          text: "[COMPANY_NAME] maintains a portfolio of alternate operating capabilities to ensure that critical business functions can be sustained regardless of the nature, scope, or duration of a disruption to the primary facility. The alternate site strategy is designed to provide layered resilience, with options ranging from immediate failover to cloud infrastructure through full physical relocation to a dedicated recovery facility.\n\nThe following alternate site categories are maintained and tested by [COMPANY_NAME]. Hot Site refers to a facility equipped with pre-installed and pre-configured technology infrastructure, including servers, network equipment, workstations, and telecommunications, capable of supporting critical operations within hours of activation. Warm Site refers to a facility with basic infrastructure (power, connectivity, environmental controls) and partial technology provisioning that can be brought to operational status within 24 to 48 hours. Cloud Recovery Environment refers to infrastructure-as-a-service and platform-as-a-service resources maintained with a qualified cloud provider, pre-configured with recovery images and data replication, enabling rapid provisioning of critical application environments. Remote Work Capability refers to the ability of personnel to perform critical functions from personal residences or other remote locations using organization-issued or approved devices, secure VPN connectivity, and cloud-based collaboration tools.\n\nThe Incident Commander shall select the appropriate alternate site option based on the damage assessment findings, the estimated duration of primary facility unavailability, the number and type of functions requiring relocation, network and telecommunications requirements, physical security and compliance considerations, and cost projections. The selection decision shall be documented and communicated to the Executive Crisis Team.\n\nPre-positioning and readiness requirements for alternate sites include: current network diagrams and configuration documentation stored on-site; tested connectivity to backup data repositories and cloud services; physical security controls including access restriction, visitor management, and surveillance; environmental controls adequate for technology equipment; sufficient workspace, furniture, and amenities for the projected recovery workforce; pre-staged supplies including paper, forms, and basic office materials; and current copies of this plan and all associated recovery procedures.\n\nThe Logistics and Facilities Lead is responsible for coordinating the physical relocation process, including personnel transportation, equipment movement, and supply procurement. The IT Recovery Lead shall verify alternate site technology readiness, establish all required network connections, and conduct system validation testing before declaring the site operational. All personnel relocated to an alternate site shall receive a briefing on site-specific procedures, including emergency exits, security protocols, and local amenities. [COMPANY_NAME] shall test alternate site activation procedures at least annually, with the results documented and used to improve readiness."
